    "body": ">If you are needing the pkgconfig files, why don't you just install using make install (not using cmake at all)?\r\n\r\nPlain makefiles are the worst option when it comes to packaging by a Linux distribution. There is no standardization. Everyone is keen on inventing 1. their own variable names (`PREFIX` vs. `prefix`), 2. funny installation paths / not heeding the FHS split between \"bin\" and \"share\" and just dumping everything into one directory, 3. mess up with the _basic_ expectations we usually get from build systems like autotools, cmake, (or whatever else there is). Like lacking a `make install` target, or, in case of grpc, I just found that it does not care about DESTDIR:\r\n\r\n```\r\n[   30s] + make install DESTDIR=/home/abuild/rpmbuild/BUILDROOT/grpc-1.9.0-0.x86_64\r\n[   33s] [INSTALL] Installing public C headers\r\n[   33s] install: cannot create directory '/usr/local/include/grpc': Permission denied\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo no. Whenever there is a build system file, distros will try to use it. We will even write one ourselves if plain makefilery is just way too bulky/complicated/faulty."
  },
