    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> If you are needing the pkgconfig files, why don't you just install using make install (not using\r\n> cmake at all)?\r\n\r\nIn addition to what @jengelh said: because the Makefiles do not install the `gRPCConfig.cmake` file either.  How the library is used (via CMake, via pkg-config, via something else) should not depend on how the library was compiled and linked.\r\n\r\n> So I am not sure if duplicating the pkgconfig files installation makes sense.\r\n\r\nSo don't.  Use CMake for all builds on Windows, Linux and macOS.  Always install the `*.pc` files (even on Windows, some folks use pkgconfig and Makefiles there too), and always install the `*.cmake` files.  You cut one build system to support (yes, I know you use templates to generate them, but still...), and your users get to use the build system that they wanted to.\r\n "
  },
