    "body": "> The cmake build scripts are meant mostly for:\r\n> \r\n> * be able to build on Windows (where cmake is our primary build system).\r\n> * to be able to integrate well with cmake based projects on other platforms (cmake is not our primary build system on Linux and Mac).\r\n> \r\n> If you are needing the pkgconfig files, why don't you just install using `make install` (not using cmake at\r\n> all)? The cmake-based install is there mostly to provide a gRPCConfig.cmake so that other cmake\r\n> based project can include gRPC using find_package(). So I am not sure if duplicating the pkgconfig \r\n>files installation makes sense.\r\n\r\n1) Not everything uses CMake (some use Autotools...to many's dismay)\r\n2) Straight-up makefiles do _**NOT**_ work worth jack on cross-compilation.\r\n\r\nI'd rather you'd do this \"right\" in the first place.  I can't get your CMake config files you generate to properly pick the right cross-compilation (You do **NOT** honor all the all of the needed things from a tools file or I'd have my problem fixed already...  You presume your pathing for libraries, etc. is from the same as the tools...which breaks all to HELL on a Yocto setup for follow-on binaries or an SDK sandbox- because your tools are in an X86 environment usually, and the other's in an ARM, MIPS, or RISC-V target sysroot...)  \r\n\r\nIf you did  both, I'd have had the ability to simply resort to pkgconfig configuration which would've honored my target sysroot in the follow on projects.  Broken, but usable.  As it stands, I'm now trying to figure out how to un-pooch what you guys've done to me. \r\n\r\n"
